BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR
It can be shown (by using a variant of Formula 10.2.7 on page 665 of Stewart's text) that the area of the surface generated by rotating the polar curve
\[r=f(\theta),\;\; a \le \theta \le b\]
where \(f'\) is continuous and \(0 \le a < b \le \pi\) about the line \(\theta=\pi/2\) is
\[S=\int_{a}^{\,b} {2\pi r \cos(\theta) \sqrt{r^2+\left(\frac{dr}{d\theta}\right)^2}}\,d\theta\]

$PAR$HR$PAR
Use the above formula to find the surface area generated by rotating the lemniscate \(r^2=\cos(2\theta)\) about the line \(\theta=\pi/2.\)

$PAR
Surface area = \{ans_rule(45)\}

END_TEXT

ANS(num_cmp("2*pi*sqrt(2)"));

